										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<h2 class="wp-block-heading">The Keep on Yeoldelands &#8211; Session 156</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><em><strong><a href="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/keep-on-yeoldelands/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Click here for the other sessions.</a> </strong></em></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<h1 class="wp-block-heading has-text-align-center">Dahn Sarf Convention &#8211; One-Off Expedition i</h1>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Bit of a change this session. I ran a game for five players in London as part of the Dahn Sarf Convention: three former and current Yeoldelands participants, and two newcomers. I&#8217;d wanted to run Waking of Willowby Hall for some time but it was tricky to slot into the campaign: having the giant and thieves waiting to be triggered into action merely by the PC&#8217;s presence feels rather arbitrary, and it would be a real push to fit into our 2.5-hour sessions (and its timer-based escape room-like doesn&#8217;t split up well across expeditions), Perfect for a longer-session one-shot, though.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">It&#8217;s quite a bit longer than normal; hopefully it might give any would-GMs of this module an idea of the structure (or at least how we went about it) which is the sort of thing I find helpful in after-action reports of published adventures. Rather than tag the GM notes on the end as usual, I think they warrant a blog post of their own. </p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Warning: clear spoilers for Waking of Willowby Hall ahead.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><em>31 Jan 2026</em></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><strong>Adventurers</strong>:</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>Bruce the Robber (Thief 1)</li>



<li>Eryck the Widely-Read (Magic User 1)</li>



<li>Ethel the Unread (Halfling 1)</li>



<li>Infirmity Jainne (Cleric 1)</li>



<li>Violent Elizabeth (Fighter 1)</li>
</ul>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">A shared debt of 3000gp had brought the adventurers to this old abandoned manor. The front door was unlocked, leading to a marbled hallway. As they were investigating the twelve pillars with curious sigils decorating each one, a distant bellowing became audible. It grew louder, and larger than any human voice had a right to be. Three more adventurers dashed in through the double doors, an angrily-honking goose under one of their arms, and they fled further into the building in an evident panic.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Poking his head outside, Eryck was greeted by a 30ft-tall figure, decked out with flowing robe and beard and swinging a large bell at the end of a chain. The magic user tentatively tried to engage him in conversation but the giant merely bellowed: “Thief! Give me back my Mildred!” and swung the bell against the hastily-shut door, making the whole building shudder. One of the marble pillars cracked and its sigil winked out of existence. Peering through one of the windows, the massive bellringer saw the party lingering as they discussed their options, and smashed the glass with his makeshift flail. The group exchanged glances and quickly determined to find that trio.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<figure data-carousel-extra='{&quot;blog_id&quot;:173068755,&quot;permalink&quot;:&quot;https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/08/the-waking-of-willowby-hall/&quot;}'  class="wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped wp-block-gallery-4 is-layout-flex wp-block-gallery-is-layout-flex">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="854" data-attachment-id="5591" data-permalink="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/08/the-waking-of-willowby-hall/2026-01-31-willowby-hall-1/" data-orig-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-1.png" data-orig-size="2737,2285" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="2026.01.31 &amp;#8211; Willowby Hall 1" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-1.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-1.png?w=656" data-id="5591" src="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-1.png?w=1024" alt="" class="wp-image-5591" srcset="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-1.png?w=1024 1024w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-1.png?w=2048 2048w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-1.png?w=150 150w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-1.png?w=300 300w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-1.png?w=768 768w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-1.png?w=1440 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>
</figure>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Two of them, including the goose-carrier, had fled up the hall’s grand staircase so the party decided to go that way. Finding a corridor with a whole lot of doors, they happened upon the pair behind their first pick. A woman held the goose under one arm, and she let go of its bill with the other to grab a staff by her side and pointed it threateningly towards the doorway.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The other woman raised a hand and a hook to try and deescalate the situation. Ignoring her sullen companion, the adventurers found out that this negotiator was Lisbet, and that she just wanted to get out of here. The giant outside was after this goose, but the concerningly-named Apocalypse Ann outright refused to part with it, and waved her arcane-looking staff menacingly. Deciding that this could only end in tears, the party backed out and decided to at least try and find something of value in case they ever did make it out.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">There were a few gold coins in the other rooms, evidently servants’ quarters, and a brown cloak. Eryck tried it on, just in case, but alas, it seemed to just be an old travelling cloak. Of more immediate interest and use were the beds which got relocated to blockade the two goose thieves in their own little room. A few muffled curses from within were punctuated by the sound of the bell once again striking the building somewhere.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">One door led to a fancier bedroom. While Ethel found some sheet music &#8211; Lavinia’s Sonnet &#8211; Elizabeth pulled out a chest from underneath the dusty old bed, and Bruce set to work with his thieves’ tools. Inside lay some fine travelling clothes (far better than Eryck’s grotty old cloak) which Elizabeth claimed and a cluster of handheld bombs. These were eagerly divided out as another bell clang shook the manor, at which point a dull crash of a heavy stone hitting the ground echoed throughout the corridors, and the fireplace in the bedroom burst into flame.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The party followed a set of stairs up to the roof, hoping to scout out a possible escape root. No such luck &#8211; the giant, while he hadn’t noticed them &#8211; would have a clear line of sight anywhere around the building, but they did find an old ballista up in the tower. Nothing to load it with, but surely they could find some makeshift missiles.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">After a quick scurry across the rooftop to examine and then disregard the beacon in the other tower, they descended back down inside and explored the library. Hearing murmurs and whispers coming from the books, Eryck unfurled one of his scrolls and cast Detect Magic. No immediately obvious magical item revealed itself, but there seemed to be a haze throughout the rooms and corridors he could see. The group left the books to their squabbles over alchemy and botany, heading to the building’s other wing.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Finding a room full of mouldy smoking jackets and a big mirror, they spied a stout fellow in a fez in the reflection with no clear source, but their musings about him were interrupted by a cry of alarm through another door, and the clash of blades. Racing through, they found the third thief desperately fighting off a large, dark-armoured figure, and they sprang to his aid.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Violent Elizabeth drew the knight’s attention, parrying its blows while the new, temporary ally was dragged to the safety of the dressing room. Realising it was an empty suit of armour they were facing, Bruce snuck up behind it, flipped up its visor and chucked his bomb inside. The ensuing bang turned the figure into a shape closer resembling a barrel, and the party were eventually able to overcome their foe. The armour crumbled into dust, and then vanished. Before they could investigate further, a bellow came from outside as the gaint, drawn by the explosion, swung his bell at the windows. They fled.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<figure data-carousel-extra='{&quot;blog_id&quot;:173068755,&quot;permalink&quot;:&quot;https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/08/the-waking-of-willowby-hall/&quot;}'  class="wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped wp-block-gallery-5 is-layout-flex wp-block-gallery-is-layout-flex">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="661" data-attachment-id="5592" data-permalink="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/08/the-waking-of-willowby-hall/2026-01-31-willowby-hall-2/" data-orig-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-2.png" data-orig-size="3276,2115" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="2026.01.31 &amp;#8211; Willowby Hall 2" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-2.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-2.png?w=656" data-id="5592" src="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-2.png?w=1024" alt="" class="wp-image-5592" srcset="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-2.png?w=1024 1024w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-2.png?w=2048 2048w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-2.png?w=150 150w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-2.png?w=300 300w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-2.png?w=768 768w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-2.png?w=1440 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>
</figure>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Back among the smoking jackets, the quivering rescuee was being fortified with a few sips of cheap wine, and he presented himself as Helmut, ally to Apocalypse Ann and Lisbet but, y’know, not that close to them. Stealing the goose had all been Ann’s idea anyway since she probably wanted all the golden eggs it laid.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Eyes shining like gold pieces, the party encouraged him to tag along with them, assuring him they could get him out safely. They asked about a supply of weapons anywhere, and he mentioned seeing a room downstairs teeming with weaponry. The quickest way there was through the western stairwell, but he refused to go back that way &#8211; that was where the dread knight had come from &#8211; so the party doubled back to the marble hall, noting nearly half the pillars were now cracked, and followed Helmut’s directions through the downstairs.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Spying a harpsichord on the way, Ethel insisted on trying out the sheet music she’d found. A disgruntled aristocratic voice interrupted her recital, and a haughty spectral lady flounced through the wall. Spotting Eryck in a servant’s cloak, she started barking out orders to move the harpiscord up the guest room like she’d asked many times already.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Affronted by the initial attitude of the party, she seemed mollified after a bit of kowtowing, limiting her threats to merely informing Lord Fenwick of their behaviour. Her responses to their queries about the manor were still snooty since she didn’t appreciate cleaning the place taking priority over moving her harpsichord, but she muttered in exasperation something about Fenwick’s wand probably still being in the dining room where he left it, before storming off in a huff.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Unfortunately for the party, as they entered the next room they realised the giant was still loitering at that end of the building, and he spied them through the window. He smashed the window and snatched up Jainne. Deciding there was little they could physically do to help her, everyone else scurried through the sitting room, calling out that, look, they’d spotted the goose over here! The huge figure flung his quarry down and gave chase. They pointed up the stairs and kept him looking up their for a moment, enough time to drag the crumpled form of their cleric into what was most definitely a weapons room. As she read off a prayer of healing from her scroll, the rest of party loaded up on as many spears as they could carry.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<figure data-carousel-extra='{&quot;blog_id&quot;:173068755,&quot;permalink&quot;:&quot;https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/08/the-waking-of-willowby-hall/&quot;}'  class="wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped wp-block-gallery-6 is-layout-flex wp-block-gallery-is-layout-flex">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="897" data-attachment-id="5593" data-permalink="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/08/the-waking-of-willowby-hall/2026-01-31-willowby-hall-3/" data-orig-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-3.png" data-orig-size="2576,2258" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="2026.01.31 &amp;#8211; Willowby Hall 3" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-3.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-3.png?w=656" data-id="5593" src="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-3.png?w=1024" alt="" class="wp-image-5593" srcset="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-3.png?w=1024 1024w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-3.png?w=2048 2048w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-3.png?w=150 150w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-3.png?w=300 300w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-3.png?w=768 768w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-3.png?w=1440 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>
</figure>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Then it occurred to them that there was a significant chunk of map with unaccounted for with no obvious entrances, and they zeroed in on a glass display case. Shifting it carefully aside, they found a hidden door which opened into an unlit room. What light they did have from the windows behind them showed a vast array of mushrooms. They picked some, reasoning there might be a book or two in the library that might give enough info to sell these on back in civilisation.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">A cry of terror from the next room on brought them back to their more immediate concerns. Opening the door they saw Lisbet locked in a struggle with an owlbear which seemed to have stepped down from a display and was attempting to savage the one-handed thief. The party urged Helmut forward to help his erstwhile companion but the fighter was very skeptical about the need for valour. They handed him a random mushroom, assuring him it would empower him with the resolve necessary.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<figure data-carousel-extra='{&quot;blog_id&quot;:173068755,&quot;permalink&quot;:&quot;https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/08/the-waking-of-willowby-hall/&quot;}'  class="wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped wp-block-gallery-7 is-layout-flex wp-block-gallery-is-layout-flex">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="868" data-attachment-id="5595" data-permalink="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/08/the-waking-of-willowby-hall/2026-01-31-willowby-hall-4/" data-orig-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-4.png" data-orig-size="2833,2404" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="2026.01.31 &amp;#8211; Willowby Hall 4" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-4.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-4.png?w=656" data-id="5595" src="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-4.png?w=1024" alt="" class="wp-image-5595" srcset="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-4.png?w=1024 1024w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-4.png?w=2048 2048w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-4.png?w=150 150w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-4.png?w=300 300w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-4.png?w=768 768w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-4.png?w=1440 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>
</figure>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Helmut munched nervously as Lisbet fought on, and suddenly a mass of rats emerged from the creaky floorboards to present themselves in formation before him. Somewhat bemused, he tentatively directed them towards the owlbear and they started swarming the monster. It, however, was unhampered by their gnawing attacks and nonchalantly cut down the thief down.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Helmut quietly closed the door on the melee between rodent and mutant hybrid, “Oh well, I tried.”</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Understandably reluctant to try that route to the eastern stairwell and ballista, the party checked to make sure the giant had moved on from the western side of the manor and crept on up to the roof. Ethel was slipping and sliding about, and seemed to be sweating a considerable amount of unpleasant slime. Apparently she’d had a nibble on another mushroom out of curiosity. She was especially careful crossing the rooftop with the others to offload their spears by the siege weapon.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">They weren’t sure it would be enough to finish off the giant, so Bruce proposed an idea for softening the great brute up.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">A little while later, the giant found himself being quietly called for. Squinting down, he saw a halfling and a human carrying the still, silent form of his goose. In stage whispers, they indicated they’d fought off the thieves and rescued her, and after her travails she’d fallen asleep. They were willing to hand her over for safe passage out. The giant, in his own booming hushed tones, indicated he wanted the thieves’ heads, but would be taking Mildred for now. Just to be safe.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<figure data-carousel-extra='{&quot;blog_id&quot;:173068755,&quot;permalink&quot;:&quot;https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/08/the-waking-of-willowby-hall/&quot;}'  class="wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped wp-block-gallery-8 is-layout-flex wp-block-gallery-is-layout-flex">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="620" data-attachment-id="5596" data-permalink="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/08/the-waking-of-willowby-hall/2026-01-31-willowby-hall-5/" data-orig-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-5.png" data-orig-size="3048,1847" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="2026.01.31 &amp;#8211; Willowby Hall 5" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-5.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-5.png?w=656" data-id="5596" src="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-5.png?w=1024" alt="" class="wp-image-5596" srcset="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-5.png?w=1024 1024w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-5.png?w=2048 2048w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-5.png?w=150 150w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-5.png?w=300 300w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-5.png?w=768 768w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.31-willowby-hall-5.png?w=1440 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>
</figure>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">As Ethel handed over the still form in the giant’s outstretched hand, Elizabeth surreptitiously lit the fuse to one of the bombs concealed in the mass of rotten wood and manky feathers taken from the various beds around the building, held together by the mushroom-induced sweaty slime. The pair raced back into the building while the enormous besieger poked suspiciously at the thing in his hand.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Upon hearing the explosion, Jainne hastily started loading the ballista with an old spear. Eryck lit the oil flask attached to it, and then resident archer Bruce launched it as the giant staggered back from the blast. His aim was true and the makeshift bolt struck his target’s shoulder, the oil smashing and splashing around the point of impact.<br>With a murderous look in his eyes and fire in beard, the giant charged the tower. Jainne flung herself to the side to avoid his grasp, but Helmut was not so quick. He was lifted high in the air, ready to be brought down with a brutal and unsurvivable splat, but the raised arm gave Bruce the perfect opening to fire another quickly-loaded spear into the giant’s heart.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">With a great crash, he toppled over backward, dropping Helmut some forty feet to the ground. Remarkably, some moans from the fighter indicated the fall hadn’t been deadly, but there was no time to worry about that now: the party dashed down to the marble hall, sure that Apocalypse Ann would have heard the commotion and try to make a break for it.<br>Sure enough, she appeared at the top of the great staircase, goose still under one arm. The party insisted she hand the goose over, believing their giant-killing efforts efforts merited a strong claim to the jackpot. Ann shrugged in response and raised her staff.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">A fireball shot towards the party who dived for cover. All were to some degree singed, but poor Jainne, still feeling the impact of the giant’s grip, was incinerated. The rogue caster tried to make a break for the door but one of Bruce’s arrows in the leg halted her escape, and Elizabeth’s greatsword separated her head from her body. Momentarily freed, the goose made to dash back further into the building but Eryck flopped down on top of it, determined not to spend a moment longer in the wretched manor.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">With the gold egg-laying goose now in their possession, the party reckoned it was just a matter of waiting until they had enough to pay off their debts. No need to risk the magically-charged Willowby Hall any further, especially with that owlbear still on the loose. They headed around outside the eastern side of the hall, ostensibly to rescue Helmut but with an eye on the giant’s quality silk robe. Unfortunately it was badly burnt but at least some of it could salvaged to pass on to a keen merchant. As they were cutting the unsinged parts away, they happened to notice a shiny gem lodged amongst the beard bristles. Packing away that and hoisting the bell between them &#8211; surely the town would pay handsomely to have that back &#8211; they made their way back through the woods towards civilisation, dragging the moaning Helmut behind them.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
