		<item>
		<title>The Keep on Yeoldelands &#8211; Session 155</title>
		<link>https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/03/the-keep-on-yeoldelands-session-155/</link>
					<comments>https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/03/the-keep-on-yeoldelands-session-155/#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Idle Doodler]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Tue, 03 Feb 2026 14:59:21 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[RPG]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Dungeons and Dragons]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Fantasy]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Old School Essentials]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Session Report]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Temple of 1000 Swords]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Yeoldelands]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/?p=5579</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Click here for the other sessions. Side Expedition 2T 29 Jan 2026 Adventurers: Pondering whether this newly discovered underground network might be the Angry Wee Folk’s route through to the Gatehouse’s mining operation, the adventurers packed their bags and set off once more for the submerged ruins. After Fezziwig had discovered the trapped alarm to &#8230; <a href="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/03/the-keep-on-yeoldelands-session-155/" class="more-link">Continue reading <span class="screen-reader-text">The Keep on Yeoldelands &#8211; Session&#160;155</span></a>]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><em><strong><a href="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/keep-on-yeoldelands/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Click here for the other sessions.</a> </strong></em></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Side Expedition 2T</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><em>29 Jan 2026</em></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><strong>Adventurers</strong>:</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>Edward (Cleric 3)</li>



<li>Elixabete (Dwarf 4)</li>



<li>Fezziwig (Thief 1)</li>



<li>Firstleaf (Elf 2)</li>



<li>Groucho (Fighter 2)</li>



<li>Hartley (Bard 2)</li>



<li>Maistlyn (Magic User 2)</li>



<li>Mike (Cleric 4)</li>



<li>Assorted NPCs: Artizar (F1), Atze (T1), Ecclesdale (F1), Mendoria (MU1), Mitxel (F1), Negu (H2)</li>
</ul>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Pondering whether this newly discovered underground network might be the Angry Wee Folk’s route through to the Gatehouse’s mining operation, the adventurers packed their bags and set off once more for the submerged ruins.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">After Fezziwig had discovered the trapped alarm to have been reset, they proceeded cautiously into the statue room. The bodies had gone, dragged off to the west, and all the many swords compiled into a single pile before the towering form. The party spread out, some watching the exits while the others examined the pile and the chamber’s walls, spotting the faint indication of a doorway hidden in the wall behind the statue.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">As Elixabete and Fezziwig checked the door for danger, a ghostly, crowned, three-eyed Kozengi form &#8211; the first non-skeletal sample they&#8217;d seen &#8211; emerged through the rock, wailing and sobbing in a distant voice. It flung itself to the ground, begging for forgiveness before disappearing. Immediately the air was filled with clangs as all the swords the party had been carrying suddenly became to heavy to bear and plunged to the ground. Unable to lift them, the party redistributed their remaining weapons to ensure most remained armed in some form, and then pushed open the hidden door.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<figure data-carousel-extra='{&quot;blog_id&quot;:173068755,&quot;permalink&quot;:&quot;https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/03/the-keep-on-yeoldelands-session-155/&quot;}'  class="wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped wp-block-gallery-9 is-layout-flex wp-block-gallery-is-layout-flex">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="738" data-attachment-id="5581" data-permalink="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/02/03/the-keep-on-yeoldelands-session-155/2026-01-29/" data-orig-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.29.png" data-orig-size="1841,1328" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="2026.01.29" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.29.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.29.png?w=656" data-id="5581" src="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.29.png?w=1024" alt="" class="wp-image-5581" srcset="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.29.png?w=1024 1024w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.29.png?w=150 150w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.29.png?w=300 300w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.29.png?w=768 768w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.29.png?w=1440 1440w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/02/2026.01.29.png 1841w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>
</figure>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">They were greeted by the sight of an enormous sandpit populated with sandy humanoid figures engaged in an endless melee, dissolving and reforming as they lost their individual bouts. Spotting another glowing sword working its way through different sedimentary opponents, the party sought a way through to grab it. Firstleaf tried striding over to it with the confidence of an official with a lanyard and a piece of paper, but he was forced to retreat in the face of a sparring partner rising from the ground to face him.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Mike and his retainers started filling helmets with water and dousing the figures, and that seemed to work, turning them to immobile mud forms, but such was the size of the pit that they had no hope of reaching any of the duellists near the centre.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Trusting in his collection of magical protections, Groucho was next to brave the pit, but he found his progress halted by more opponents rising up. He edged back to safety, drawing all the sandy figures towards the doorway, and the rest of the party sprang to his aid, cutting through the duellists and grabbing the blade.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">After emptying their boots of sand, the adventurers found that their own swords were once again usable but decided to return to town anyway to investigate this trio of sigil-marked blades they’d discovered.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">GM Notes</h3>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>Not my strongest GM performance: a lot of head space was taken up with mentally preparing for running a game at the Dahn Sarf convention in two days’ time, so didn’t feel quite as at ease with last-minute changes of plans. The players had discussed heading further afield to find some elves who might be able to grant them access to some higher-level magic firepower to deal with the Snake-Armed Goddess’ statue, and I had to plead for a bit more warning; my head wasn’t in the game for a fully improvised session. The players seemed happy to go back to Plan A.</li>
</ul>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
