	</item>
		<item>
		<title>The Keep on Yeoldelands &#8211; Session 153</title>
		<link>https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/01/21/the-keep-on-yeoldelands-session-153/</link>
					<comments>https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/01/21/the-keep-on-yeoldelands-session-153/#respond</comments>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Idle Doodler]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 21 Jan 2026 06:58:00 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[RPG]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Dungeons and Dragons]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Fantasy]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Gatehouse on Cormac's Crag]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Old School Essentials]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Session Report]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Yeoldelands]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">http://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/?p=5553</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[Click here for the other sessions. Side Expedition 2R 15 Jan 2026 Adventurers: There was more loot to be found in the collapsed chambers, the adventurers were sure, so they loaded up on supplies and headed once more for the Gatehouse. They looked out for but saw no sign of their hairy scout, Grutz. Making &#8230; <a href="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/01/21/the-keep-on-yeoldelands-session-153/" class="more-link">Continue reading <span class="screen-reader-text">The Keep on Yeoldelands &#8211; Session&#160;153</span></a>]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[
<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><em><strong><a href="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/keep-on-yeoldelands/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener">Click here for the other sessions.</a> </strong></em></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Side Expedition 2R</h2>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><em>15 Jan 2026</em></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"><strong>Adventurers</strong>:</p>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>Edward (Cleric 3)</li>



<li>Elixabete (Dwarf 4)</li>



<li>Firstleaf (Elf 2)</li>



<li>Groucho (Fighter 1)</li>



<li>Hartley (Bard 1)</li>



<li>Mike (Cleric 4)</li>



<li>Assorted NPCs: Ecclesdale (F1), Flintoffden (MU1), Mendoria (MU1), Mitxel (F1), Negu (H2),</li>
</ul>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">There was more loot to be found in the collapsed chambers, the adventurers were sure, so they loaded up on supplies and headed once more for the Gatehouse. They looked out for but saw no sign of their hairy scout, Grutz.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Making a detour for the copper mine, the party pondered what to do with the chained skeleton wreathed in blue flames. A few were willing to release him now they had the means to do so, but the majority were against the idea, either out suspicion of the prisoner’s true nature or because they were unwilling to risk losing the enchanted gems. Eventually Groucho stepped forward with his magical spear and put the skeleton out of his misery. The flames vanished, the chains shattered and the gems lost their power anyway.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Under Elixabete’s dwarven guidance, the party spent the next three days working their way around the Four-Armed Goddess’ temple, carefully avoiding the trapped statue. They spotted a hidden compartment and drew out a snake-shaped staff, but that was all the loot they discovered. Firstleaf went slightly insane after studying some dodgy serpent-like glyphs for too long, and a room of a former priestess yielded nothing but some crude stone jewellery.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Conscious of the chests of coins they’d seen in the goddess’ main room, they decided to try their luck with the statue once again. They used the snake staff to bind two of its arms and hacked away at it but the narrow space they were able to clear hampered their efforts. As the statue started wrenching itself free from the rubble, grabbing Groucho and hurling him against the rocks, the adventurers decided beat a retreat.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<figure data-carousel-extra='{&quot;blog_id&quot;:173068755,&quot;permalink&quot;:&quot;https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/01/21/the-keep-on-yeoldelands-session-153/&quot;}'  class="wp-block-gallery has-nested-images columns-default is-cropped wp-block-gallery-13 is-layout-flex wp-block-gallery-is-layout-flex">
<figure class="wp-block-image size-large"><img loading="lazy" width="1024" height="636" data-attachment-id="5554" data-permalink="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/2026/01/21/the-keep-on-yeoldelands-session-153/2026-01-15/" data-orig-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/2026.01.15.png" data-orig-size="3213,1996" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="2026.01.15" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/2026.01.15.png?w=300" data-large-file="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/2026.01.15.png?w=656" data-id="5554" src="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/2026.01.15.png?w=1024" alt="" class="wp-image-5554" srcset="https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/2026.01.15.png?w=1024 1024w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/2026.01.15.png?w=2048 2048w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/2026.01.15.png?w=150 150w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/2026.01.15.png?w=300 300w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/2026.01.15.png?w=768 768w, https://therecouldhavebeensnakes.wordpress.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/2026.01.15.png?w=1440 1440w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></figure>
</figure>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">As they scampered back down to Fourtowers Bridge, cliff on one side and woods on the other, they were held up by a dozen armed thugs. A voice called from the trees, declaring that there were more out of sight and that the party should for everyone’s sake lay down whatever the riches they’d unearthed from the Gatehouse and leave peacefully. The adventurers charged.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">Crossbow bolts flew from the treeline, injuring several of the party and killing Flintoffden, before they crashed into the line of spears. Mendoria’s arcane drowsiness again came in handy, downing most of the visible foes while Firstleaf’s armour of ethereability allowed him to dash into the wood and try and draw some of the ranged attacks. He unfurled a scroll to trap several of them while his companions ran to join him, having dealt with the first dozen.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">As the unstuck brigands scarpered further into the woods, a fancily-armoured and near-invisibly-cloaked woman leapt down from a tree; she hurled an oil flask onto the web, roasting the trapped bandits, and winked out of sight. Firstleaf’s keen elven eyes just about spied her reappearing far away amongst the trees, joining her fleeing companions.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph">The party gathered up their fallen retainer and returned to the safety of the village, leaving the dead scoundrels for the wildlife.</p>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">GM Notes</h3>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li>The characters’ adventures have largely been confined to dungeons; it’s been a while since they have come across a violent encounter outdoors. (Largely this has been because I’ve just not rolled that many. Pretty sure these dice need to take the saltwater test.) I’ve been modifying the possible encounters according to party actions just like with the underground tables, modifying some entries or replacing them with other, more appropriate ones. And I’ve now finally started noting them down in the campaign scrapbook again &#8211; fewer rifling through papers going forward, hopefully.</li>
</ul>



<p class="wp-block-paragraph"></p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
